passages.text: Energy Macro Monthly August Data

In the oil market, prices remain pressure by concerns over inventory balances into 4Q25 / 1Q26 and the onset of Autumn refinery maintenance. In gas, prices have declined due to faster- than- expected storage injections in Europe and increased (sanctioned) LNG sales from Russia. Refining margins showed mixed trends and diverging regional margins in Renewable Diesel (RD): European RD margin improved, US RD margin weakened.

Oil Demand. Since our July update (LINK), oil price declined by \(9\%\) , driven by overhanging concern on accelerated OPEC+ unwind and surplus inventory balances into 4Q25/1Q26 and the commencement of Autumn refinery maintenance, which were partially offset by growing market optimism around a potential Fed rate cut in September and ongoing mutual attacks of Russia/Ukraine on energy infrastructures.

Chinese oil demand data for July decreased by \(1\%\) y/y (0.1mmb/d y/y Ex 12), mainly driven by diesel \((- 0.2mmb / d y / y / - 5\%)\) and gasoline \((- 0.1mmb / d y / y / - 4\%)\) . YTD Chinese oil demand is up \(2\%\) y/y (0.3mmb/d y/y), mainly driven by naphtha (0.1mmb/d / 4%) and Bitumen (0.04mmb/d / 7%). Crude oil imports fell by 1.0mmb/d, or \(8\%\) m/m (Ex. 13) with runs declining to 14.9mmb/d (- 0.3mmb/d m/m) driven by reduced throughput at private mega refineries, which were partially offset by improved runs at NOCs and teapots. Looking ahead, rising maintenance is expected to impact NOC operations, though this will partially offset by SPR builds (up to 140 mmb from Jul- 25 to Mar- 26), which support demand outlook for the remainder of the year (IEA +0.1mmb/d y/y | JEFE +0.1mmb/d y/y), and the gradual ramp up of Yulong (second reformer commenced in July) and the Daxie expansion (restarted in August after a pause in July following initial testing).

US crude and products stocks showed an 8mmb draw / 9mmb build in the past four weeks vs. 8mmb draw / 3mmb draw during the same period last year (based on weekly EIA data; Ex. 3). US Diesel demand 4- week moving average increased marginally, by 3kb/d, or \(0.1\%\) y/y, while gasoline demand decreased by 63kb/d, or \(0.6\%\) y/y (Ex. 21- 22). In Europe, total oil products demand increased by 0.3mmb/d y/y, or \(0.5\%\) in June, mainly driven by increases in gasoline (+0.1mmb/d y/y / + 5%, Ex. 26) and diesel (+0.1mmb/d y/y / + 2%, Ex. 25). The uptick in demand reflects improving conditions in the eurozone economy (Ex. 28).

OPEC+ Supply. Crude production declined m/m in July by 0.23mmb/d, led by decreases in Saudi Arabia (0.08mmb/d m/m), Venezuela (- 0.11mmb/d m/m) and the Kazakhstan (- 0.05mmb/d m/m), offset by increases in Iran (+0.19mmb/d m/m) and the UAE (+0.06mmb/d m/m). Overall, OPEC+ compliance improved m/m (Ex. 46), mainly due to KSA and Kazakhstan.

With OPEC+ intending to complete its full unwind in September, the market has been seeing a strong build into 4Q25. On our expert call with Energy Aspects, Amrita Sen discussed how they expect the 2.5mmb/d OPEC+ supply increase to result in an actual supply increase of 2mmb/d (LINK), 2.1mmb/d based on their latest estimate (JEFE 2.0mmb/d). However, recent attention has been tuned to the ability of the group to ramp production accordingly. Recent data per EA's OilX data has shown OPEC8+ Aug exports 0.58mmb/d higher vs March (before unwind | vs 1.9mmb/d intended or 1.5mmb/d post- compensation). Besides, Russia's production stood at 9.2mmb/d in July (target 9.2mmb/d | Post- compensation target 9.1mmb/d), but future ramp- up could be challenged by depleted fields, reduced capex amid sanctions. Continues inside...

The recent US- Russia summit has resulted in no commitment to an immediate ceasefire. The subsequent US- Ukraine meeting resulted in President Trump pushing for a bilateral meeting between President Zelensky and President Putin, to be followed by a trilateral summit including Trump. Following recent developments, the US administration has discussed imposing \(50\%\) tariffs on India from buying Russian oil (EA estimates state- owned refiners import \(0.6 - 0.7mm / d\) ); and conflict have intensified with Ukraine ramp up attacks on Russia energy facilities creating supply risk, including: 1) Druzhba's Southern leg (Unecha pumping station led to a potential offline period of up to five days sustained outage could impact \(\sim 0.5mm / d\) crude flows into Europe, which includes Belarus \(\sim 0.3mm / d\) , Slovakia and Hungary \(\sim 0.1mm / d\) each); 2) Refinery Strikes (including UstLuga and Novoshakhtinsk).

Non- OPEC+ Supply. The latest US crude production data (May) indicates a marginal \(0.1mm / d\) increase m/m \((+0.7\%)\) , reaching \(13.5mm / d\) (latest PSM data, Ex. 37). The latest forecasts by our US team show liquids production growing in 2025 at \(0.5mm / d\) , mainly driven by Permian and \(\sim 3\%\) capital efficiency growth (LINK). Our US team has flagged a general trend of Capex reductions across E&P companies ( \(\sim 3\%\) capex cut with no change to oil production, LINK).

Brazil's production increased by \(0.08mm / d\) m/m \((+0.35mm / d\) y/y) to \(3.76mm / d\) ) in June due to ramp- up in Buzios (FPSO Almirante Tamandaré) and Mero (FSPO Alexandre de Gusmão) fields. We estimate Brazil's oil production will grow by \(0.3mm / d\) y/y and \(0.2mm / d\) y/y in 2025 and 2026 (IEA 0.36mm/d in 2025 | 0.16mm/d in 2026).

On a project basis, Non- OPEC+ capacity scheduled to start up in 2025 and 2026 amounts to \(\sim 2.5mm / d\) and \(\sim 1.2mm / d\) , respectively, which we estimate will contribute to production growth of \(\sim 1.6mm / d\) and \(1.7mm / d\) in 2025 and 2026 (Ex. 46) before accounting for underlying mature assets decline.

Global Natural Gas. Since our last update last month, TTF prices have shown declined (cal- 25- 1%, cal- 26- 5%). This reflects a stronger- than- expected inventory injections across Europe, European Council's adoption of more flexible gas storage and speculation on Russia ability to sell sanctioned LNG following the arrival of US- sanctioned Arctic LNG 2 tanker in China, which was partially offset by heightened geopolitical risk (intensified Russian attacks threatening Ukraine's gas infrastructure).

North West European gas demand shows decline y/y: In the last 21 weeks (injection period from week 14), demand was \(3\%\) lower y/y or \(11mm / d\) (1.6bcm). Industrial demand showed a y/y decrease in Germany (down \(6\%\) or \(7mm / d\) , injection period to week 33, Ex. 70), while France saw a y/y decrease (down \(10\%\) or \(2.4mm / d\) , injection period to week 34). European inventories are building below the 5- year average: As of August 24th, overall storage stood at 85bcm ( \(\sim 76\%\) full), \(8\%\) (8bcm) below the 5- yr avg and \(17\%\) (17bcm) lower than 2024 levels (Ex. 63- 66). However, the European Commission introducing flexibility on gas storage targets provides some relief into the pace of inventory build (attain \(90\%\) storage between 1- Oct and 1- Dec; with \(10\%\) flexibility on difficult conditions / additional \(5\%\) under unfavourable market). Getting to \(80\%\) and \(90\%\) storage utilization down 1 would require additional injections of 5bcm ( \(\sim 0.5bcm / week\) ) and 16bcm ( \(\sim 1.6bcm / week\) ), respectively.

We continue to see a tight market in '25, due to higher European injection demand, lost Russian pipeline imports ( \(\sim 15bcm / yr\) ), and LNG project delays. LNG supply additions from project start- ups and ramp- ups - including start- ups and ramp- ups at Plaquemines, Corpus Christi Stage 3, Tortue FLNG (first LNG in April- 25), and LNG Canada (first LNG in June- 25) - will barely match Europe's incremental LNG import requirements (Ex. 98- 99). QatarEnergy has now indicated that first LNG from North Field East is expected by mid- 26 (Energy Aspects adjusting start dates for NFE and NFS

On the LNG trade flow front, European imports are up \(\sim 16m\) t y/y YTD (or \(+27\%\) , Ex. 68), partially offset by Asian Pacific LNG imports, \(\sim 10m\) (lower y/y (or - 7% Ex. 75 and 80- 83): China (- 8mt y/y, or - 18%); S. Korea (+1mt y/y, or \(+2\%\) ); India (- 2mt y/y, or - 15%); Taiwan (+1mt y/y, or \(+9\%\) ); Japan (+0.3mt y/y, or \(+1\%\) ). The reduction in Chinese LNG imports doesn't reflect falling demand (minimal decline y/y, despite a warmer winter) but rather higher pipeline imports, domestic gas production, and storage withdrawals. Global liquefaction planned outages at \(\sim 0.5m\) t in August (- 0.1mt m/m, Ex. 96), mainly due to LNG outages in Australia (Ichthys and Gladstone). Recent pipeline flows into LNG Canada averaged \(>180mmcf / d\) (from Willow Valley/Sunset Creek- West that feed into the Coastal GasLink pipeline, LINK) over the past week, which corroborates SHEL's comment that ramp- up has been as expected. Into 2H, multiple Australia LNGs would be entering planned maintenance (Gladstone, APLNG, Gorgon and Ichthys).

US Gas. US storage stood at 3.2tcf (90bcm) as of 15- August, \(6\%\) above the 5- yr avg and \(3\%\) below 2024 levels (Ex. 84- 86). A recent expert event co- hosted by our US team highlighted: 1) positive contracting outlook given LNG's role in trade negotiations; 2) pre- FID US LNG projects are increasingly looking to sell down stakes in their projects to improve financing (LINK).

Refining. As of 26 August, margins show mixed trends m/m across regions. The USGC LLS 3- 2- 1 margin decreased by \(\) 0.9\(/bbl m / m, or 4\%; Northwest Europe (NWE) Brent 3 - 1 - 2 decreased by\) \ \(0.7/\) bbl m/m, or \(3\%\) . In Asia, the Minas 3- 2- 1 decreased by \(\) 2.0\(/bbl m / m, or 17\% (Ex. 100 - 105).\)

Global refinery runs reached 84.4mb/d in June, reflecting a \(\sim 0.5mmb / d\) or \(0.6\%\) y/y increase (YTD to June, Ex. 106- 111): North America (+0.3mmb/d y/y YTD, or \(1\%\) ), Europe (- 0.2mmb/d y/y YTD, or - \(1\%\) ), Asia (largely flat YTD), and Africa (+0.3mmb/d y/y YTD, or \(+15\%\) ).
In the US, utilization rates has increased by \(5\%\) y/y in August (at \(97\%\) ). In China, teapot refiners held steady at \(\sim 48\%\) in August (vs. \(50\%\) in 2024).

In 2025, refinery additions are expected to be heavily concentrated in the Asia Pacific region (accounting for \(\sim 76\%\) of global additions of \(1.3mmb / d\) , of which \(\sim 80\%\) will come from China, primarily from petchem- integrated sites, including Panjin, Yulong, and Zhenhai). Global capacity closures are expected to outpace additions by \(0.1mmb / d\) and will be more evenly distributed across regions (Ex. 126- 129); with continued issues at Dangote (RFCC maintenance through end- Aug), however, Dos Bocas has indicated signs of ramping up production (running at \(0.19mmb / d\) vs \(0.34mmb / d\) at full capacity) faster than anticipated, and cabotage waivers has been granted in July to ease shipping capacity constraints.

Renewable Diesel - Margin strength. European renewable diesel margins are showing a continued improving trend: In August, European HVO- UCO margin rose by \(\sim\) 560/t m/m, marking an \(6\%\) increase. YTD performance up by \(\sim\) 160/t y/y, or \(27\%\) .

Feedstock prices increased in August QTD, with UCO FOB ARA and PFAD FOB Indonesia increased by \(\) 81/t m/m\(\) (4\%) and\) \ \(82/t m/m\) (4\%), respectively (Ex. 131). In the US, renewable diesel margins have weakened m/m in August, driven by lower Diesel and D4RIN values, alongside higher UCO feedstock costs, which were partially offset by higher LCFS (Ex. 134).

US D4 RIN Generation data in July decreased by \(81mm\) gallons / 135mn units (24%) y/y and decreased by \(11mm\) gallons / 20mn units (4%) m/m, within which no RD imports were made into the US, Ex. 135). In August, the EPA resolved a long- standing backlog of Small Refinery Exemption (SRE) petitions, out of 5.34bn RINs that are exempt, only \(\sim 1.4bn\) can be used to meet 2024 compliance obligations; while the remaining 3.96bn are eligible for non- exempted pre- 2023 obligations (LINK).

Buy - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of \(15\%\) or more within a 12- month period.

Hold - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of plus \(15\%\) or minus \(10\%\) within a 12- month period. Underperform - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of minus \(10\%\) or less within a 12- month period. The expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) for Buy rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) is \(20\%\) or more within a 12- month period as these companies are typically more volatile than the overall stock market. For Hold rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) , the expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) is plus or minus \(20\%\) within a 12- month period. For Underperform rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) , the expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) is minus \(20\%\) or less within a 12- month period.

Jefferies Franchise Picks will include only Buy rated stocks and the number can vary depending on analyst recommendations for inclusion.
